<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Future of the BBC</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Scottish Newspaper Society [FBB0055]</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Writte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n evidence submitted by John McL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ellan, director of the Scottish Newspaper Society</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, on behalf of SNS members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As director of the Scottish Newspaper Society, I represent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the interests of the Scottish n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ewspaper industry, comprising both the Scottish titles in the ownership of UK-wide publishers and the ten independent indigenous companies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In total there are eight Scottish daily titles, four Sundays  and 97 weeklies. The S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NS also represents the interests of the UK nationals with Scottish editions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Scottish newspaper industry remains concerned about the effect ‘free’ BBC digital services has and will continue to have on their businesses.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With the BBC Trust clearly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">expressing a desire for the Corporation to expand its local digital services it is inevitable such provision will run into those provided by other commercial news and information providers.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">And with more newspapers examining pay-walls in order both to dri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve up digital revenues and to limit cannibalisation of content, an expansion of BBC services will make this more difficult than it already is.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Previously, companies were really only concerned about desktop services, but now the development of mobile appli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cations is an essential part of their future strategic direction. With the benefit of the licence fee, the BBC is in a far stronger position to develop such services in a way commercial companies cannot.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the past, the BBC had plans to recruit up to 36 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local digital journalists to populate local sites in six Scottish regions but this was shelved when the increase in the licence fee was capped. We fear such plans are merely shelved but not scrapped altogether.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But the impact of the BBC is not limited to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the development of new, sophisticated means of communication. In small, isolated communities like the Northern Isles the effect of the BBC’s presence can be considerable.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In both Orkney and Shetland, the BBC has a dedicated radio station but the operations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are not limited to broadcast or indeed on its own digital platforms. With the use of social media like Facebook, the BBC is now publishing material which previously would have been the preserve o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f the local Press, The Orcadian</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and The Shetland Times.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Loc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al events can be publicised on the BBC’s Facebook page where before they would have featured in the pages of the local papers. These would not necessarily have been paid-for adverts but part of the rich fabric of local news coverage which has maintained th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eir popularity.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Both of those independent publishers are essential elements of the island community life, and the papers are the corner stones of solid local publishing businesses producing books, leaflets and posters which support local employment. These</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> too are under pressure from cheap producers in Eastern Europe.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BBC Scotland has given us an assurance that local digital development is not high on their agenda, and while that is true now we fear that after the referendum in 2014 that might change.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">course, in the event of a ‘Yes’ vote, the entire future of the BBC in Scotland will become part of the negotiation process  between the Scottish and UK governments, but after a ‘No’ vote BBC Scotland will inevitably reappraise its operations.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are conce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rned that at that point, with the encouragement of the BBC Trust, the development of local digital will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be very much back on the agenda.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of course the BBC has a vital role to play in the tapestry of communication in Scotland and we support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the majority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> what they do. But their role should be to provide quality services which would otherwise not be possible on a commercial basis.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It should not be the BBC’s role to identify services which others are pioneering and then to use any signs of success as a jus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tification for entering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and distorting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emerging markets. We find it perverse that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any sign of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commercial success should be interpreted by the BBC as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proof that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">license fee payers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">receive such services for free.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>